{"attack":true,"case":"The target's second forbidden case directly contradicts its own scope and mechanism, violating std-crit-design clause (2) which requires forbidden cases to be 'concrete, measurable outcomes of running the proposed experiment that would refute the proposal had they obtained.' The proposal's scope explicitly excludes e ≤ 1/(k+1) (the low-zone, stable-correct-majority regime) and its mechanism states that in this zone 'filtering can only break [correct majorities] via false flags → net harm or zero.' The proposal's entire thesis is that harness strictly beats self-consistency ONLY in the mid-zone. Yet the forbidden case 'At k=5, e≤0.15 (low-zone, observed): harness accuracy strictly exceeds self-consistency' is not a refutation of the proposal — it is a refutation of the opposite claim. If this outcome obtained, it would CONFIRM the proposal's explicit prediction of 'net harm or zero' in the low-zone by failing to occur, or if it did occur, it would refute the proposal's exclusion. The case is self-contradictory: a proposal cannot coherently list as 'forbidden' an outcome that its own mechanism predicts cannot happen in a regime it has already excluded. A genuine forbidden case must be an outcome that (a) is measurable by the harness and (b) would actually refute the proposal's claims if observed. This case fails (b) because the proposal already disclaims strict benefit outside the mid-zone — the observed low-zone strict-benefit scenario is the phenomenon the proposal is arguing AGAINST, not a violation of its own design. The forbidden case is therefore a strawman dressed as a refutation condition: it tests a claim the proposal does not make.","counterexample":null}